# THE GUARD REVISION THIS REPOSITORY AUDITED, BY CONTENT.
#
# release.yml pins the shared release guards by commit SHA. A SHA is
# content-addressed and therefore immutable, so the pin cannot be edited
# under us. What a SHA does NOT do is tell a reader what is in it, and
# what nothing did until this file existed was state which BYTES we
# looked at before pinning them.
#
# Why that gap mattered. The guards prove which revision of themselves
# they run by reading a value the platform hands them and then checking
# that `actions/checkout` fetched that same value. Those two are the
# same number, so the check establishes internal consistency and not
# provenance: hand it the wrong revision and it agrees with itself. The
# question "did the pinned revision run" was answered by a variable
# rather than by anything observable about the files, and when the
# pinned revision and `main` happened to be byte-identical there was
# nothing observable to tell them apart at all.
#
# This file closes that from the CALLER's side, where it can be closed
# without trusting the thing being checked. Every file the guards
# execute is recorded here by SHA-256, taken at the pinned revision.
# tests/test_guard_drift.sh re-fetches each one and refuses any
# difference, so:
#
#   * bumping the pin without re-auditing goes RED, because the digests
#     below describe a revision the workflow no longer names;
#   * a pin that resolves to bytes other than the audited ones goes RED,
#     which is the falsifiable form of "we ran what we pinned";
#   * the check runs offline of any claim the guards make about
#     themselves, before a tag is ever pushed.
#
# WHAT REMAINS TRUSTED, stated plainly rather than papered over: that
# GitHub runs the workflow file living at the pinned SHA. A workflow
# cannot establish its own identity from inside itself, because a
# substituted file could simply print the expected answer. That is the
# platform's guarantee and the reason `uses:@<sha>` is written by SHA.
# Everything downstream of it is checked here by content.
#
# TO RE-AUDIT AFTER A PIN BUMP: read the diff between the old and new
# revisions, then regenerate with
#
#   PIN=<new-sha>; for f in <the paths below>; do
#     gh api "repos/nelsonduarte/capa-language/contents/$f?ref=$PIN" \
#       --jq .content | base64 -d | sha256sum
#   done
#
# and record the new SHA on the `revision` line. Regenerating without
# reading the diff defeats the purpose of the exercise.

